# Claude Context — User Story Writing Guide

*v3.0 — Enhanced with PPT/Excel reference patterns and anti-pattern examples*

Internal reference for writing and reviewing user stories in this product repo. Follow this guide precisely.

---

## 1. Document Structure

Every user story document must include the following sections, in order:

### Header Metadata Table

| Field | Notes |
|---|---|
| **Document Version** | e.g. v0.1 — First Draft or v3.0 — First Draft |
| **Date** | DD MMM YYYY format |
| **Author** | First name + initial |
| **Sprint** | Sprint name and date range in brackets e.g. [Feb 16 to March 17] |
| **Dependency** | Only include if the feature depends on another feature/build |

### Sections (in order)

- **Context & Problem Statement** — 1–3 short paragraphs. What exists today, what the problem is, and what this feature solves. This is one section — do not split into separate "Background", "Goal", or "Problem Statement" headings. Do not repeat the same information under different labels.
- **User Stories** — One H3 section per user persona (e.g. End User, Admin, Manager, System).
- **Edge Cases** — Bullet list of edge cases with resolution for each.
- **Non-Functional Requirements** — Performance, latency, async behaviour, and any open questions to the team.
- **Next Steps** (optional) — Follow-up actions, owners tagged with @name.

---

## 2. User Story Format

Each user story follows this pattern:

> As a [Persona], I want to [action], so that [outcome].

Followed immediately by Acceptance Criteria as a numbered list.

### Rules for Acceptance Criteria

- Write in plain English. No technical jargon unless unavoidable.
- Each item is a complete, testable condition.
- Use **bold** to highlight **UI element names, column names, error messages, and key terms**.
- Nested bullets are allowed for sub-conditions or step sequences (Step 0, Step 1, Step 2...).
- Error messages must be written out verbatim in quotes, e.g. **"Edited value ([X]) exceeds the maximum allowable pay-out ([Y]) for this row."**
- Where a condition has design implications, add an inline tag: **Chetana —** followed by the design note.
- Where a condition has tech/backend implications, add an inline tag: **Pooja / tech team —** or the relevant owner's name.
- When AC references an external specification (e.g. an Excel with event definitions, a validation list, a schema), cite the exact file name. **Do not write vague AC like "All 31 events are firing correctly."** Write: "All events listed in [PostHog_Event_Taxonomy_v2.xlsx] are firing correctly, with properties matching the data types and values specified in that file."

