## 3. Personas Used

Use these persona names consistently. Do not invent new ones without checking with the team.

| Persona | Description |
|---|---|
| **End User / Participant** | Salesperson, retailer, mechanic, or other enrolled individual in a campaign |
| **Reporting Manager / Manager / ABM** | Manager who oversees participants; may or may not be enrolled themselves |
| **Distributor** | User assigned to distribute targets or points to participants at a given node (see Type B and Type D target distribution) |
| **Campaign Owner / Client Admin** | Configures campaign settings, uploads matrices, manages incentive calculations |
| **Admin / GRG Admin / Product Admin** | Configures campaigns, dashboards, and platform-level settings. Controls activity-based permissions (e.g. M105) |
| **System** | Used when the story describes automated/backend behaviour with no human actor |

---

## 4. Tone & Language Rules

- **Use present tense throughout** ("the system displays", not "the system will display").
- **Be specific and literal** — avoid vague phrases like "the user can see relevant data."
- **Name exact pages** when describing UI flows, e.g. **Settings > Dashboards > Homepage Builder**.
- **Name existing features explicitly**, e.g. "same flow as metric card picking unique identifier" or "exactly similar to points awarding in Type B campaign".
- **Grooming edits** — tag with **[GROOMING EDIT]** followed by a brief note. Highlight in orange in Word docs.
- **Cross-reference by feature name and campaign type**, e.g. "This is similar to Type D without the last section — Approval Flow After Calculations."

---

## 5. Tables

Use markdown tables for:

- Default variables per campaign type
- Metadata headers
- Any mapping of persona → behaviour → options
- **Data schema definitions** — column name, description, data type, and source (see Section 12)
- **Widget/variable configuration tables** — widget type, variable, click destination, required variables (see Section 13)

Tables must have a bold header row. Column headers should be short and unambiguous.

