## 8. What to Avoid

### 8.1 Structural Anti-Patterns

- ❌ **Do not write stories in future tense** ("will be able to").
- ❌ **Do not combine multiple personas** into one user story.
- ❌ **Do not skip edge cases** — every non-trivial flow must have at least one edge case documented.
- ❌ **Do not use generic placeholder text** like "TBD" — use @person to confirm instead.
- ❌ **Do not write AC as a paragraph** — always use a numbered list.
- ❌ **Do not restart AC numbering per persona** — number continuously across the whole document so grooming can reference specific items.
- ❌ **Do not omit communication codes** — when a feature triggers notifications, reference the exact communication code (see Section 10).
- ❌ **Do not omit activity codes** — when a feature is gated by permissions, reference the exact activity code (see Section 11).
- ❌ **Do not define data schemas in prose** — use a table with Column Name, Description, and Data Type (see Section 12).

### 8.2 Content Repetition Anti-Patterns

- ❌ **Do not split context into separate sections.** "Background", "Goal", "Problem Statement", and "Core Pain Point" are all the same thing. Write one Context & Problem Statement section. If you find yourself writing the same point under two headings, delete one.
- ❌ **Do not include tool explainers.** A user story is not onboarding documentation. Do not include sections like "What is PostHog?" or "What is an Event?" — the audience already knows the tools.
- ❌ **Do not include "Expected Outcomes" as a section.** Aspirational statements like "clear visibility into user journeys" are not testable. If the outcome matters, express it as a measurable NFR (e.g. "Analyst can filter events by user_id and date range in PostHog within 5 seconds").
- ❌ **Do not include "What [Team] Needs to Do" sections.** Implementation instructions ("Implement all events", "Use snake_case") are not AC. AC describes what the system does when complete, not how the team builds it. Coding standards belong in the team's engineering guidelines, not in the user story.

### 8.3 Example and Scenario Anti-Patterns

- ❌ **Do not include inline examples that duplicate a reference file.** If the event taxonomy lives in an Excel, the story should reference that Excel — not reproduce a sample event with properties. Duplication creates drift when the spec is updated.
- ❌ **Do not write scenarios that simply restate the core flow.** If your AC already says "User selects from dropdown OR enters free text," then a scenario showing "User selects from dropdown" is redundant. Only include scenarios that test edge cases not already covered by AC.
- ❌ **Do not use fictional or unrealistic values in examples.** If the actual dropdown values are "Account holder name mismatched", "Duplicate User", "Document error" — do not write a scenario using "Invoice missing" as a dropdown selection. Every example must use real values from the actual feature spec or validation lists defined in the story.

### 8.4 Anti-Pattern Reference: Stories That Don't Meet Standard

**U210113** — Missing metadata table, user story as a bullet not full sentence, AC without numbers, sections labelled "Problem" and "Goal" instead of Context & Problem Statement, variables in a table but no AC for configuration, edge cases without resolutions.

**PostHog Phase 1 story** — Separate "Background & Goal" and "Core Pain Point" sections (repetitive), tool explainer ("What is PostHog?"), inline event example duplicating the reference Excel, "What Tech/Analyst Team Needs to Do" section (implementation instructions), "Expected Outcomes" section (aspirational, not testable), vague AC ("All 31 events are firing correctly" without referencing the spec file).

**U210105 L1 Data Cleanliness** — Scenario 1 and 2 restate the core user flow already described in AC (select from dropdown / enter free text), and Scenario 1 uses "Invoice missing" as a dropdown value despite it not being in the actual validation lists. Only Scenario 3 (deleted dropdown option with historical data) is a genuine edge case that adds value beyond the AC.

