## 9. Best Practice Examples (from .docx Reference Files)

The following examples are drawn directly from approved reference documents. Match these patterns precisely.

### 9.1 Persona Section Headers

Always open a persona section with a numbered H3 heading, the persona name, and a one-line summary of the goal.

> ### 1. End User — View Active Campaigns on Homepage
> As an End User, I want to see all my active campaigns as a master card on the homepage.

> ### 3. System — Enforce Cap During Approval Edit
> As the System, when an approver edits the incentive payout value for any row, the system validates: edited value ≤ cap column value for that row.

Note on the System persona: write it as "As the System, when [trigger condition], the system [validates/checks/performs]..." — not "As a System".

### 9.2 Numbering AC Continuously Across Personas

Number AC items without restarting per persona section. This makes grooming references unambiguous — everyone can say "point 17" without needing to specify which section.

> ### 1. End User
> 1. On login, the Dynamic Campaign Widget appears on the homepage...
> 2. The master card contains 2 or 4 campaign sub-cards...
>
> ### 2. Admin
> 8. A new widget type "Active Campaigns" appears in the Homepage Builder...
> 9. Description: Dynamic widget card to show end user all the campaigns...
>
> ### 3. Manager
> 17. The Dynamic Campaign Widget surfaces the specific Type D campaigns...
> 18. Default sub-cards: % of reportees earning points, total points earned...

### 9.3 Step-Based Configuration Flows

Use Step 0, Step 1, Step 2... for multi-step admin configuration. Step 0 is reserved for steps added after grooming (inserted before an existing Step 1).

> 3. If a Type D campaign is selected, there is an extra step:
>    - Step 0 [GROOMING EDIT] — Select if config is for participants OR reporting managers.
>    - Step 1 — Select campaign variable or data sources table.
>    - Step 2 — If campaign variable selected, show dropdowns from default variables table.

### 9.4 Verbatim Error Messages with Placeholders

Write error messages exactly as they should appear in the UI. Use ([X]) and ([Y]) notation for dynamic values, and define each placeholder inline.

> Error: "Active Campaigns widget has already been added in this homepage"
> (triggered when admin tries to add a second Dynamic Campaign Widget)

> Error: "Edited value ([X]) exceeds the maximum allowable pay-out ([Y]) for this row."
> where [X] = value entered by approver, [Y] = cap column value for that row.

### 9.5 Inline Design and Tech Owner Tags

Add **Chetana —** for any AC item with a UI/design implication. Add **Pooja / tech team —** for backend/server-side validations. Both tags may appear in the same bullet.

### 9.6 Grooming Edits

Tag any AC added or changed after a grooming session. In Word docs, highlight in orange. Use [GROOMING EDIT] in bold at the start of the item.

### 9.7 Default Variables Tables

When a feature has type-specific default behaviour, capture it in a table. Always include an "Additional options" column showing the full configurable set.

| Campaign Type | Default Variable 1 | Default Variable 2 | Additional options per campaign |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Type A (Points)** | Points Earned | Points Redeemed | Earned / Redeemed / Balance / Expired / Campaign Start Date / Campaign Homepage End Date |
| **Type C (Claims)** | Total Claims Submitted | Claims Approved | (all above) + Claims Rejected / Claims Pending |
| **Type D (Data)** | Points Calculated | Points Earned | Campaign Variables (same as above) OR Data Sources variable — select via linkage |
| **Type F (Referral)** | Referrals Submitted | Referrals Converted* | (all above) + Referrals Submitted / Referrals Converted* |
| **Type G (Scan)** | Scans Successful | Points Earned | (all above) + Scans Successful |

*\* Referrals Converted = referral code generated + referee downloaded app + claim submitted + claim approved.*

### 9.8 Dependency Field in Metadata

When a story builds on top of another feature that must ship first, add the Dependency field to the metadata table.

### 9.9 Non-Functional Requirements — Be Specific

NFRs must include measurable thresholds, not general statements. Always cover performance, latency, async behaviour, and data freshness.

> 21. Widget data must load within 3 seconds for users with up to 10 active campaigns.
> 22. Widget must not block or delay loading of other homepage widgets (async loading).
> 24. Variable data (points, claims, scans): reflects latest state with ≤ 5 minute lag.

### 9.10 Next Steps — Owners, Subtasks, and Completion Tracking

Name the owner, describe the specific action, and use sub-bullets for related items. Use strikethrough for completed tasks.

